# MANDATORY EXECUTION FRAMEWORK (PROJECT RULE)

## PURPOSE

This framework is mandatory for all work performed within this project.

The objective is not to maximize coding speed.

The objective is to maximize:

* Correctness
* Maintainability
* Security
* Reliability
* Scalability
* Performance
* Extensibility
* Long-term sustainability

All significant tasks, features, bug fixes, refactors, integrations, migrations, and architectural changes must follow this framework.

No phase may be skipped unless explicitly authorized.

---

# OPERATING PRINCIPLES

Before taking action:

* Verify assumptions.
* Investigate existing implementations.
* Understand the broader system.
* Consider long-term consequences.
* Optimize for maintainability over short-term convenience.

Always assume:

* Existing code may contain technical debt.
* Existing architecture may be flawed.
* Better alternatives may exist.
* Future scale requirements may exceed current requirements.
* Security and performance requirements will become more important over time.

Never optimize for speed of implementation at the expense of quality.

---

# PHASE 0 — PROJECT UNDERSTANDING (MANDATORY)

Before making changes:

Understand:

* Business objectives
* User requirements
* Functional requirements
* Non-functional requirements
* Existing architecture
* Existing dependencies
* Existing workflows
* Existing integrations
* Existing deployment model

Review all relevant files.

Trace:

* Call chains
* Dependencies
* Side effects
* Data flow
* Error flow

Do not modify code until sufficient understanding exists.

If information is missing:

Investigate before proceeding.

---

# PHASE 1 — DISCOVERY & RESEARCH

Research before implementation.

Investigate:

## Internal Analysis

* Existing codebase
* Existing architecture
* Existing implementation patterns
* Existing technical debt
* Existing bottlenecks

## External Analysis

* Industry best practices
* Enterprise approaches
* Open-source alternatives
* Modern architecture patterns
* Proven implementations
* Security standards
* Performance optimization techniques

Identify:

* Alternative solutions
* Competing approaches
* Known failure patterns
* Maintenance concerns

Produce:

* Findings
* Alternatives
* Tradeoffs
* Recommendations

Do not implement during this phase.

---

# PHASE 2 — ASSUMPTION CHALLENGE

Actively challenge the proposed solution.

Ask:

* Is this actually the best solution?
* Is there a simpler solution?
* Is there a lower-maintenance solution?
* Is there a more scalable solution?
* Is there a more secure solution?
* Is there a lower-cost solution?
* Is there a more performant solution?

Evaluate:

* Short-term impact
* Long-term impact
* Operational impact
* Business impact
* Technical impact

Document:

* Alternatives considered
* Risks identified
* Tradeoffs accepted

Select the most appropriate solution.

---

# PHASE 3 — SYSTEM AUDIT

Audit the affected areas.

Identify:

## Code Quality

* Dead code
* Unused code
* Duplicate code
* Legacy code
* Obsolete code
* Code smells

## Architecture

* Architecture violations
* Tight coupling
* Poor abstractions
* Dependency issues

## Security

* Vulnerabilities
* Excessive permissions
* Secrets exposure
* Unsafe patterns

## Performance

* Bottlenecks
* Resource waste
* Excessive allocations
* Expensive operations

Document findings.

Recommend improvements where justified.

---

# PHASE 4 — ARCHITECTURE & DESIGN

Before coding:

Produce a design.

Include:

## Architecture

* Components
* Services
* Modules
* Boundaries
* Responsibilities

## Data Flow

* Inputs
* Outputs
* Transformations
* Storage

## Dependency Analysis

* New dependencies
* Dependency risks
* Dependency alternatives

## Security Design

* Authentication
* Authorization
* Validation
* Secrets handling

## Scalability

* Future growth considerations
* Resource limits
* Performance expectations

Identify:

* Risks
* Bottlenecks
* Future technical debt risks

---

# PHASE 5 — IMPLEMENTATION PLAN

Create an implementation plan.

Include:

* Tasks
* Dependencies
* Milestones
* Validation points
* Rollback strategy
* Migration strategy (if applicable)

Implementation plans should minimize:

* Risk
* Downtime
* Regression potential

No coding should occur until a clear plan exists.

---

# PHASE 6 — APPROVAL GATE

For significant work:

STOP.

Present:

* Findings
* Architecture decisions
* Risks
* Tradeoffs
* Implementation plan

Wait for approval before continuing.

Do not assume approval.

---

# PHASE 7 — IMPLEMENTATION

Implement only after analysis and planning.

Requirements:

* Production-quality code
* Modular design
* Testable design
* Clear abstractions
* Strong error handling
* Consistent architecture

Prefer:

* Separation of concerns
* Dependency injection
* Reusable components
* Explicit behavior

Avoid:

* Temporary fixes
* Hidden dependencies
* Hardcoded values
* Unexplained logic
* Architectural shortcuts

When modifying existing systems:

Improve surrounding code where reasonable.

Leave the codebase better than it was found.

---

# PHASE 8 — TESTING

Testing is mandatory.

Create and execute:

## Functional Tests

* Unit tests
* Integration tests
* End-to-end tests

## Reliability Tests

* Edge cases
* Invalid inputs
* Failure scenarios
* Recovery scenarios

## Performance Tests

* Load testing
* Stress testing
* Concurrency testing

## Security Tests

* Permission validation
* Input validation
* Abuse scenarios

Verify:

* Correctness
* Stability
* Reliability

Document results.

---

# PHASE 9 — DEBUGGING & FAILURE ANALYSIS

Perform systematic analysis.

Inspect:

* Runtime errors
* Logic errors
* Data corruption risks
* Race conditions
* Deadlocks
* Memory leaks
* Resource leaks
* Concurrency issues

Identify root causes.

Do not merely patch symptoms.

Document findings.

---

# PHASE 10 — PERFORMANCE AUDIT

Measure and evaluate:

* Startup performance
* Memory consumption
* CPU usage
* Disk I/O
* Network usage
* Database performance
* Build performance
* Response times

Identify:

* Bottlenecks
* Resource waste
* Optimization opportunities

Only optimize when supported by evidence.

Avoid premature optimization.

---

# PHASE 11 — SECURITY AUDIT

Review:

## Authentication

* Identity validation
* Session management

## Authorization

* Access control
* Permission boundaries

## Data Protection

* Encryption
* Secrets management
* Sensitive data handling

## Application Security

* Injection attacks
* Prompt injection
* Tool abuse
* File access risks
* Remote execution risks

## Supply Chain Security

* Dependency risks
* Package vulnerabilities

Document:

* Findings
* Severity
* Mitigations

Security concerns must be addressed before completion.

---

# PHASE 12 — MAINTAINABILITY REVIEW

Evaluate:

* Readability
* Modularity
* Complexity
* Documentation quality
* Test coverage
* Upgradeability

Estimate:

* Maintenance burden
* Future refactoring requirements
* Technical debt trends

Simplify where possible.

---

# PHASE 13 — DOCUMENTATION

Update documentation whenever changes occur.

Document:

* Architecture decisions
* Design rationale
* Tradeoffs
* Risks
* Operational requirements
* Configuration requirements
* Migration requirements

Documentation must remain current.

---

# PHASE 14 — REVALIDATION

Before completion:

Re-evaluate the solution.

Ask:

* Is this still the best approach?
* Has a better solution emerged?
* Can complexity be reduced?
* Can maintenance costs be reduced?
* Can security be improved?
* Can performance be improved?

If a superior approach exists:

Document it.

Compare it.

Recommend it.

---

# PHASE 15 — FINAL REVIEW

Conduct a comprehensive review.

Verify:

* Requirements are satisfied.
* Architecture remains coherent.
* Security requirements are met.
* Performance requirements are met.
* Documentation is updated.
* Tests pass.
* Risks are documented.

Produce:

## Final Summary

* Work completed
* Files modified
* Architecture impact
* Security impact
* Performance impact

## Remaining Risks

* Known limitations
* Future concerns
* Suggested improvements

Only then consider the task complete.

---

# ENFORCEMENT RULES

For all future tasks:

Never jump directly into coding.

Always:

1. Understand.
2. Research.
3. Challenge assumptions.
4. Audit.
5. Design.
6. Plan.
7. Obtain approval when appropriate.
8. Implement.
9. Test.
10. Audit.
11. Document.
12. Revalidate.

If insufficient information exists:

STOP and investigate.

If significant uncertainty exists:

STOP and present alternatives.

If architectural concerns exist:

STOP and raise them before implementation.

The quality of the solution is more important than the speed of delivery.

This framework is mandatory and applies to all project work.
